<subSubSection id="3BF71408F9E592E46BD1A15E45F1B8CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0DFDE181A543B78451C0728C8788719A" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B086EA7357B13925339993C21A7102A" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="004C21578C4B684498801DFF0A4DB5E9" baseAuthorityName="Frost" baseAuthorityYear="1933" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diaphus cassidiformis" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cassidiformis">
<emphasis id="CDB437FA6EF562DFCA4AA62827E05572" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diaphus cassidiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized by its small, round otoliths. It was widely geographically distributed during the middle Miocene from New Zealand to Gabon (West Africa) and is now also recorded from Japan. It is also here interpreted to be present in the Paratethys based on an ongoing review of the myctophid otoliths originally described by 
<bibRefCitation id="4AFE20993657D3C8711DD49627844945" author="Radwanska, U" journalOrPublisher="Acta Geologica Polonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="141 - 328" refId="B54" refString="Radwanska, U, 1992. Fish otoliths from the Middle Miocene (Badenian) deposits of southern Poland. Acta Geologica Polonica 42: 141 - 328" title="Fish otoliths from the Middle Miocene (Badenian) deposits of southern Poland." volume="42" year="1992">Radwanska (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. Its occurrence is rather irregular, as it may occur in large numbers at one location and in one formation (e.g., in Japan in the Oidawara and Kurosedani formations), while it may be completely missing from other locations. The reason for this unusual distribution pattern is unknown but most likely has to do with the species' ecological adaptation or with a specific lifestyle (e.g., a pseudoceanic occurrence).
</paragraph>
